Now I have all the scan data. Let me compile the findings for this hot-path code.

---

## .NET Performance Review — `TimeSpanFormatting.cs`

**Context:** Logging framework, millions of calls/minute — all code treated as hot path.

### Scan Execution Checklist

| Recipe | Hits |
|--------|------|
| `.ToLower()`/`.ToUpper()` | 1 |
| `params` | 1 (1 method) |
| `.Replace()` chains | 0 |
| LINQ operators (`.Select`/`.Where`/`.Take`/`.Any`/`.Aggregate`) | 17 |
| `.ToList()` | 1 |
| `.ToArray()` | 1 |
| `new List<` | 1 |
| `Enumerable.Reverse` | 1 |
| Unsealed classes | 1 of 1 |
| Sealed classes | 0 |
| `static readonly Dictionary<` | 0 |

### Positive Findings

- ✅ `new List<string?>(8)` — pre-sized capacity on L91
- ✅ No `string.Substring()`, `string.Replace()`, or `IndexOf` without `StringComparison`
- ✅ No async anti-patterns, no `HttpClient`/`Regex` issues

---

### Findings

#### 1. LINQ chain allocations on hot path (17 instances)

**Impact:** Each LINQ operator (`.Where()`, `.Select()`, `.Take()`, `.Any()`, `.Aggregate()`) allocates an enumerator object and a delegate. At millions of calls/min, this is **tens of millions of avoidable GC allocations/min**.

**Files:** `TimeSpanFormatting.cs:L128` (`.Any()`), `L140,L143,L146,L149` (`.Where().Take().Where()` + list materialization), `L158,L169` (`.Where().ToList()` + `.Take()`), `L244,L261-262,L270-272,L284` (`.Select().Where().ToArray()`), `L304` (`.Aggregate()`)

**Fix:** Replace all LINQ chains with `foreach` loops. Example for `SetPrecisionOfTimeSpan`:

```csharp
private static List<string?> SetPrecisionOfTimeSpan(
    List<string?> timeParts, int precision, bool countEmptyUnits)
{
    var result = new List<string?>(precision);
    int count = 0;
    foreach (var part in timeParts)
    {
        if (count >= precision) break;
        if (countEmptyUnits) count++;
        if (part != null)
        {
            if (!countEmptyUnits) count++;
            result.Add(part);
        }
    }
    return result;
}
```

Similarly for `IsContainingOnlyNullValue` — replace `.Any()` with a simple `foreach`:

```csharp
private static bool IsContainingOnlyNullValue(List<string?> timeParts)
{
    foreach (var part in timeParts)
        if (part != null) return false;
    return true;
}
```

#### 2. `enum.ToString().ToLowerInvariant()` per unit (up to 8× per call)

**Impact:** `ToString()` on an enum boxes the value and allocates a string via reflection lookup. `.ToLowerInvariant()` allocates a second string. At 8 units × millions of calls = **~16M+ string allocations/min**.

**Files:** `TimeSpanFormatting.cs:L175`

**Fix:** Pre-compute a static lookup array:

```csharp
private static readonly string[] UnitNames =
[
    "year", "month", "week", "day", "hour", "minute", "second", "millisecond"
];

private static string FormatTimePart(int value, TimeUnit unit, CultureInfo culture)
{
    var unitName = UnitNames[(int)unit];
    return value == 1 ? $"{value} {unitName}" : $"{value} {unitName}s";
}
```

#### 3. `params IStringTransformer[]` array allocation (1 instance)

**Impact:** Every call allocates a `T[]` even for the common single-transformer case. At scale, this is **one array allocation per call**.

**Files:** `TimeSpanFormatting.cs:L303`

**Fix:** Add a 1-arg overload for the common case:

```csharp
public static string Transform(
    this string input, CultureInfo culture, IStringTransformer transformer) =>
    transformer.Transform(input);
```

#### 4. Unsealed class (1 of 1 classes)

**Impact:** JIT cannot devirtualize `virtual` method calls on `DefaultCollectionFormatter`. Virtual dispatch is up to **500× slower** than direct calls.

